snippet.textDisplay:
Amir Khusro wrote poetry in Farsi and in a local language. The local (Delhi) language of the commoners was Braj Bhasha but the outsiders called it Hindustani. Khusro called it Hindvi. Local nobility was adamant in keeping it pure and so they tried. How Urdu evolved from Hindustani and how is it being ‘selected’ out of India now, is a separate subject. Since late 1700s, the British started to put both languages in one bucket as Hindustani with an emphasis on Urdu script. The prevalence of word Hindi surfaced in 19th century. 

Khusro kept a conspicuous partition between the two languages by writing in their respective native scripts. He could not avoid tempering with pure Farsi sounds which were not supported in Nagari script when writing in Hindvi. The unsupported Farsi sounds in this song are in Baazi, Nizaam and Khusro. He had to change them to Baaji, Nijaam and Khusro (Kh as in Khaal (skin)). Various transcriptions of this songs indicate, this was a Kh as in Khaal (skin) in the original inscription. I have seen many online images of Urdu version where the name Khusro is transcribed as (کھسرو). The current Devanagari adaptation of Khusro’s name (ख़ुसरो) was not available to him. By the way, Khusro inherited Hindvi from his maternal grandparents. He proudly called himself a Hindustani Turk. 

Keep in mind, the oral traditions in this part of the world had been very strong. Today’s Urdu script was not developed yet to support the sounds of local language. You do not see the tinkering of indigenous  words in this song. This indicates, the original song was written in Hindustani. I have yet to find an Urdu/Hindi poem from Khusro where he used an uncorrupted word that were only supported by Farsi-Nastaleeq script. Sorry to all my Indian and Pakistani friends. Add this to candid discussion on the shared heritage.

-- After the Indian Councils Act of 1861, the government started to promote Hindustani as Urdu, especially when the Raj consolidated itself in Awadh  and Northwestern provinces. As a parts of demands from Hindu politicians, Urdu and Hindi were adopted as two official vernaculars in the 1935 constitution. Until 1947, both languages had very little differences except for the written scripts. After the Independence,  the insertion of Sanskrit vocabulary started to appear in Hindi curricula. However, the Bombay film industry kepts its traditional language, which was close to Urdu,  with a formal category as Hindi films.
